113668450.review:
Really enjoyable game if you're looking for an refreshing twist on the ever nostalgic monster collection realm.

Pros:
- Very flexible and configurable so you can mostly play how you want;
- Quite forgiving when it comes to failing - you can simply try again or come back later, no "Game Over" so it's very chill to play;
- Extremely customizable skill trees and monster parties, with in-game indications of strengths and weaknesses. There's also a pretty good wiki if you want to min/max but it's totally optional;
- Monster builds can be fine-tuned with equipment and other options beyond simply choosing the right moves/skills;
- Quite easy to level up simply by progressing/exploring. The only "grindy" part is getting eggs for monsters in new areas.

Cons:
- Navigating the map gets dull halfway through the game. There's always new monsters to find and capture, but it gets boring especially when you need to backtrack. To make things worse, secret loot is usually very unremarkable;
- Dialogues are lackluster, even though the backstory is quite interesting. Most characters are a bit too obvious and forgettable, and the player doesn't have a voice at all;
- Evolutions could be way more interesting. It feels weird that your spectral (and supposedly very special) familiar doesn't evolve into a stronger form. It feels unfortunately very replaceable, which doesn't fit into the lore.
